{"key":"post-10686892","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10686892</id>\n<content>Cotton was, and still is used in Asia to seal plastic autoclavable bags.&amp;nbsp; The early bag teks even after the internet came out all had cotton stuffed into the openings on the bags.&amp;nbsp; I agree polyfill is better because it's synthetic, but cotton doesn't automatically contaminate just because it's natural.&amp;nbsp; The cotton gets sterilized along with the substrate, and the part that's exposed to the substrate moisture is on the sterile side.&amp;nbsp; The outside that's exposed to the air dries out.&amp;nbsp; As said, it's still being used today, and the Chinese are supplying 80% of all the shiitake sold in America, so it must work.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In line with the modern era, I use filter patch autoclavable bags with a tyvek filter impulse sealed to them from the factory.&amp;nbsp; I get two uses from each bag, which halves the cost.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>10686821</prev>\n<first>10684635</first>\n<last>10686892</last>\n<when>1247754951</when>\n<utime>07/16/09 05:35 PM</utime>\n</post>"}